# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pitcher
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The **12–6 curveball** is a type of pitch thrown in baseball.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] It is categorized as a breaking ball because of its downward break.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The 12–6 curveball, unlike the normal curveball (also referred to as the "11 to 5 curve" or a "2 to 8 curve" for its motion), breaks in a downward motion in a straight line.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] This explains the name "12–6", because the break of the pitch refers to the ball breaking from the 12 o'clock position to 6 o'clock on a clock face.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] While the 11–5 and 2–8 variations are very effective pitches, they are less effective than a true 12–6, because the ball will break into the heart of the bat more readily.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The pitch is used throughout Major League Baseball.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] It has several nicknames, including the "yellow hammer" and "drop curveball".
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The 12 to 6 curveball is the toughest type of curveball to hit, because it moves vertically, and has no horizontal break.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The difference of the speed from a fastball and the break make the pitch difficult to hit if a pitcher uses it correctly in a pitching sequence.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The 12 to 6 curveball is usually pitched from the overhand motion, as a three-quarters or sidearm delivery would cause the ball to break 2 to 8 instead of 12 to 6.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The sharp vertical break on the 12–6 curveball is created when pitchers apply topspin to the ball with their fingers in the process of releasing it.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] Depending on the situation and the type of pitcher, the 12–6 curveball may be more or less effective.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The effectiveness of the pitch also depends on the ability of the pitcher to apply topspin to the ball, creating movement.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] When stats for a high level pitcher's average 12 to 6 curveball are factored in, the 12 to 6 and the 11 to 5 are much more effective than Major League Baseball's average throwers of the pitch due to the pitcher's high level of ability for that pitch.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The 12–6 curveball is thrown similarly to most curveballs.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The pitch is generally thrown using a four-seam grip, in which the middle finger on the pitcher's throwing hand is placed in the gap between the two seams on the right side, and the index finger is placed directly next to it.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The pitcher's thumb is placed directly on the bottom of the baseball.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] This grip allows the pitcher to create a high amount of topspin while still having a good control of the pitch.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] The pitch is then thrown with an exaggerated 12–6 motion with both the middle finger and the thumb simultaneously helping move the baseball towards home plate, while the pitcher's index finger giving the ball topspin.
[src:pitcher/12-6-curveball] This extensive combination of mechanics makes this one of the most difficult pitches to master.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:pitcher/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The series is the 46th in league history.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The series was broadcast by Fox and Fox Sports 1 in the United States, with Fox airing Game 1 and Fox Sports 1 airing Games 2–6.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Sportsnet, a property of Blue Jays owner Rogers Communications, simulcast Fox and Fox Sports 1's coverage in Canada.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Game 1 took place on October 16, and the series ended with the Royals winning Game 6 on October 23.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] This was the second ALCS matchup between Kansas City and Toronto; the Royals previously rallied from a 3–1 deficit to defeat the Blue Jays in seven games in the 1985 ALCS.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Royals would go on to defeat the New York Mets in the World Series in five games, winning their first World Series championship in 30 years.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Kansas City Royals finished the season with a 95–67 record, winning the American League Central division title for the first time since that division was created in 1994.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Their season win total was the most since winning 97 games in 1980.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Royals defeated the Houston Astros in five games in the 2015 American League Division Series (ALDS), advancing to their second straight ALCS and eighth overall.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Toronto Blue Jays made it to the postseason for the first time since winning the 1993 World Series, finishing the season 93–69 to clinch the American League East title.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Playing in their first ALDS in team history, the Blue Jays overcame a 2–0 deficit to defeat the Texas Rangers in five games and move on to the ALCS.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] It was their first ALCS appearance since 1993, and sixth overall.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Blue Jays won four of seven games against the Royals in the 2015 regular season.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] This was the second time in seven ALCS appearances the Royals held home field advantage.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The other was 1977, when Kansas City lost Games 4 and 5 of the best-of-5 series at Royals Stadium to the eventual World Series champion New York Yankees.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Kansas City opened the scoring in the third inning off Marco Estrada when Alex Gordon hit a leadoff double and scored on Alcides Escobar's one-out double, then after a groundout, Escobar scored on Lorenzo Cain's single.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Salvador Pérez added a home run in the fourth to give the Royals a 3–0 lead.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] In the eighth, a hit-by-pitch and single off LaTroy Hawkins was followed by Eric Hosmer's RBI double and Kendrys Morales's sacrifice fly to make it 5–0 Royals.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Meanwhile, Edinson Vólquez pitched six scoreless innings, surrendering only two hits to earn his first postseason win.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Royals' touted bullpen completed the shutout, making this just the sixth time all season that Toronto was held to no runs.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] This game marked the fourth time that the Royals rallied back from a multi-run deficit to win in this post-season.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Blue Jays struck first in the third on back-to-back leadoff doubles by Kevin Pillar and Ryan Goins off starter Yordano Ventura.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] They made it 3–0 in the sixth when Edwin Encarnacion followed a leadoff single and walk with an RBI single, then Troy Tulowitzki hit a one-out RBI double.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Going into the 7th inning, David Price had retired 18 consecutive batters since a leadoff single to Alcides Escobar in the bottom of the first inning.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] However, Ben Zobrist led off the seventh inning with a pop-up to shallow right field; second baseman Ryan Goins tracked the ball back and waved off charging right fielder José Bautista, but inexplicably ducked out of the way at the last moment and allowed the ball to drop for a single.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After Lorenzo Cain singled, Eric Hosmer's single, Kendrys Morales's groundout, and Mike Moustakas's single scored a run each to tie the game.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After Salvador Perez struck out, Alex Gordon's RBI double put the Royals up 4–3.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Aaron Sanchez relieved Price and allowed an RBI single to Alex Rios.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Royals added another run in the eighth when Moustakas followed back-to-back two-out walks off Aaron Loup with an RBI single Wade Davis pitched a scoreless ninth despite allowing a leadoff single and walk as the Royals' 6–3 win gave them a 2–0 series lead.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] This was David Price's seventh consecutive playoff loss, tying him with Randy Johnson for the all-time record.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] He did record 18 consecutive outs, setting a Blue Jays franchise record.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Toronto's high powered offense finally came to life in Game 3.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After the Royals scored a run in the first off Marcus Stroman when Alcides Escobar hit a leadoff triple and scored on Ben Zobrist's groundout, Ryan Goins's single with runners on second and third put the Blue Jays up 2–1 in the third.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After a walk, Josh Donaldson's RBI single made it 3–1 Blue Jays.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Royals cut the lead to 3–2 in the third when Eric Hosmer hit into a forceout at second with runners on first and third, but the Blue Jays blew the game open in the bottom half.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After a leadoff single and walk, Troy Tulowitzki's three-run home run made it 6–2 Blue Jays.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Russell Martin then walked and scored on Kevin Pillar's double.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Kris Medlen relieved Cueto and after getting two outs, allowed a home run to Josh Donaldson to make it 9–2.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] In the fifth, Stroman's wild pitch with runners on second and third made it 9–3, then after a walk, Mike Moustakas's RBI single made it 9–4 Blue Jays, who added another run in the bottom of the inning on Ryan Goins's home run.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] They added another run in the eighth on José Bautista's RBI single with two on off Franklin Morales.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] In the ninth, Liam Hendriks allowed a leadoff single and subsequent double.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After Lorenzo Cain's sacrifice fly and Hosmer's single scored a run each, Roberto Osuna relieved Hendriks and allowed a two-run home run to Kendrys Morales before retiring the next two batters to end the game.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Dickey early in Game 4, with a two-run home run from the second batter of the game, Ben Zobrist.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After a walk, stolen base, and single, a passed ball scored another run for the Royals, then after a groundout, Mike Moustakas's sacrifice fly made it 4–0.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Alex Rios's home run made it 5–0 next inning and Dickey was pulled from the game after allowing a walk and hit-by-pitch.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Kansas City put up 5 total runs in the first 2 innings to chase Dickey from the game.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Liam Hendriks entered in as the long reliever for the Blue Jays and pitched 4.1 scoreless innings from the second to the sixth and finished with 13 outs from 12 batters faced, breaking the playoff record for more-outs-than-batters-faced performances.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Jim Lindsey previously held the mark with eight outs from seven batters faced in 1930, while playing for the St.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Royals starter Chris Young, who had split time in the starting rotation and the bullpen, pitched 4+2⁄3 innings.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Blue Jays scored their only runs of the game in the third on Josh Donaldson's ground-rule double with runners on first and second followed by José Bautista's sacrifice fly.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Kansas City's bullpen then shut the Blue Jays down for the rest of the game.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Meanwhile, the Royals' offense exploded, adding nine runs in the final three innings.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] In the seventh, after LaTroy Hawkins allowed a walk and two singles to load the bases with no outs, Alcides Escobar hit a sacrifice fly off Ryan Tepera, who then threw a wild pitch to let another run score.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After Ben Zobrist walked, Lorenzo Cain's RBI single and Eric Hosmer's sacrifice fly scored a run each.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Next inning, the Royals loaded the bases off Tepera when Escobar hit another sacrifice fly, then a single reloaded the bases before Cain's two-run single made it 12–2 Royals.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] In an effort to save his bullpen and to the amusement of some fans and players, Toronto manager John Gibbons elected to bring utility infielder Cliff Pennington to pitch the top of the ninth with two on and two outs.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] This marked the first time that a position player pitched in a playoff game.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Pennington allowed a single to load the bases before Escobar's two-run single capped the game's scoring at 14–2 Royals.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Franklin Morales pitched a scoreless bottom of the ninth to give the Royals a 3–1 series lead.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Game 5 appeared to be a pitchers' duel early on.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Toronto starter Marco Estrada and Kansas City starter Edinson Vólquez dominated early on, with the first run of the game on Chris Colabello's home run in the second.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Things began to unwind for Volquez in the bottom of the sixth as he walked two batters and hit a third to load the bases.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Volquez then walked Edwin Encarnación to force in a run.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] With Troy Tulowitzki coming to the plate, Royals manager Ned Yost opted to pull Volquez in favor of Kelvin Herrera; however, Tulowitzki promptly lined a bases-clearing double off the center-field wall to make the score 5–0.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] That proved to be more than enough for Estrada, who only surrendered a home run from Salvador Pérez with two outs in the eighth in his 7+2⁄3 innings of work.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Blue Jays added to their lead off Danny Duffy, who allowed back-to-back two-out doubles in the seventh to Josh Donaldson and José Bautista, then a one-out single to Tulowitzki in the eighth and RBI double to Kevin Pillar.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Roberto Osuna pitched a perfect ninth to keep Toronto's season alive and send the series back to Kansas City.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] This would be the final postseason game played with sliding pits instead of a traditional full dirt infield, as the Blue Jays would install a new dirt infield at Rogers Centre prior to the start of the 2016 season.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Ben Zobrist opened the scoring two batters into the bottom of the 1st with a home run to left field off David Price.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Mike Moustakas added another home run for Kansas City in the 2nd inning, but this one was not without controversy.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] It was a liner right at the right-center field wall, where a fan reached out and caught the ball at the top corner of the wall.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The ball was initially ruled a home run, but Toronto wanted the play reviewed.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Fox commentary crew of Joe Buck, Harold Reynolds, and Tom Verducci seemed confident that the ruling would be overturned, but the ruling of a home run stood with the play being too close to overturn.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Buck, Reynolds, and Verducci would later call it a good call by the reviewing crew upon viewing further replays and upon fully understanding the configuration of the outfield wall, but debated the call several times throughout the broadcast.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Toronto got on the board in the fourth when José Bautista blasted a home run off the Royals Hall of Fame sign in left field.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Blue Jays would threaten again in the fifth when starter Yordano Ventura gave up consecutive walks to lead off the inning.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] However, he settled down and induced two pop-outs, which then brought up eventual AL MVP Josh Donaldson.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Donaldson hit a hard line-drive towards 3rd base, but Moustakas was able to come up with a spectacular diving catch to end the inning.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] In the bottom of the seventh, Moustakas reached base on a broken bat blooper to center-field.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Salvador Pérez next hit a deep fly ball to left field.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Left fielder Ben Revere then one-upped Moustakas' earlier catch with a leaping catch at the top of the left-field wall.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Revere then tried to double up Moustakas at 1st, but Moustakas got back in time to leave it at one out.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Ryan Goins then kept the good defense going by making a sliding stop on a hard Alex Gordon grounder to get Gordon out at 1st, to make it two outs, but Moustakas reached 2nd on the play.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] At this point David Price was taken out of the game in favor of right hander Aaron Sanchez to face Alex Ríos.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] On a 1-2 pitch, Rios hammered a ball to left field for a single that drove in Moustakas to give Kansas City a 3–1 lead.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] In the top of the eighth, Kansas City manager Ned Yost brought in Ryan Madson to get the Royals through the inning after Kelvin Herrera kept Toronto scoreless for the last 1+2⁄3 innings.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Yost would say after the game he put in Madson because of the impending rain: he didn't want to bring in closer Wade Davis early in case there was a lengthy rain delay which could prevent him from pitching the 9th.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Revere hit a high chopper to Alcides Escobar and beat the throw to 1st base for a lead-off infield single.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Up next was Josh Donaldson, but he remained hitless on the night when Madson got him to strike out for the first out.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Madson faced Bautista next who promptly blasted a two-run home run down the left-field line to tie the game at 3.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Madson then walked Edwin Encarnación, forcing Yost to pull Madson from the game in favor of Wade Davis.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Davis induced a pop-out from Chris Colabello, before throwing a wild pitch against Troy Tulowitzki which allowed Encarnacion to advance to 2nd.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] It was only Davis' second wild pitch of the season.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Facing a 3-2 count against Tulowitzki, the rain started to fall in Kansas City.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Davis got Tulowitzki to swing and miss for a strike out to end the inning, but Yost's fears came true as the grounds crew brought out the tarp for a rain delay, meaning Davis would have a lengthy wait between pitching appearances if he was even able to return depending on the length of the delay.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After a 45-minute rain delay, Toronto manager John Gibbons sent out closer Roberto Osuna to pitch the bottom of the eighth.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Lorenzo Cain worked an 8-pitch walk to get on base.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Eric Hosmer was up next and worked a 2-2 count before driving a ball to the right field corner for a hit, and Cain ran on contact.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Bautista fielded the ball and threw to second while Cain was flying around the base.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] As soon as Royals third base coach Mike Jirschele saw Bautista throw to 2nd, he waved Cain home.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] By the time the throw reached second base, Cain was already well past third and by the time Tulowitzki's throw to home reached catcher Russell Martin, Cain was sliding past home for the go-ahead run.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] It was the second time of the 2015 post-season that Cain had scored from first base on a single from Hosmer.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] On the play, Cain went from 1st to home in under 10.5 seconds.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Davis came back in to pitch the top of the ninth after having waited just over an hour between in-game pitches.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Martin greeted Davis with his first hit of the series on a single to center-field.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Dalton Pompey then came in to run for Martin and promptly stole 2nd base to put the tying run in scoring position.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Then on a 2-2 pitch into the dirt to Kevin Pillar, Pompey stole third and Perez could not scoop up the ball to even make a throw.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] That put a runner on third with no outs and a 3-2 count to Pillar.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] After a foul ball, Davis missed on a pitch inside to walk Pillar to put runners on the corners with no outs.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Dioner Navarro came in to pinch-hit for Goins with Toronto needing a catcher to replace Martin.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] On a 1-1 pitch, Davis got a called strike that was high and outside.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] The Toronto dugout not only started complaining about that, but they believed Davis should've been called for a quick pitch balk, which would have brought the tying run home.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Instead it was a 1-2 count and Davis got Navarro to swing and miss for the first out.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] However, Pillar stole 2nd on the pitch to leave the Royals without a double-play chance and thus putting two runners in scoring position.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] That brought up Revere who worked a 2-1 count when Davis threw a called strike, which appeared to be a ball, to make it a 2-2 count.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] On the next pitch, Revere swung and missed for the second strikeout of the inning, bringing up Donaldson with two runners in scoring position in a 4–3 game.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] On a 2-1 pitch Donaldson grounded out to 3rd for the final out to clinch back-to-back AL Pennants for the Kansas City Royals.
[src:pitcher/2015-american-league-championship-series] Alcides Escobar, who batted .478 in the series with 2 doubles and a triple, was named 2015 ALCS MVP.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The **2018 American League Division Series** were two best-of-five-game series in Major League Baseball’s (MLB) 2018 postseason to determine the participating teams of the 2018 American League Championship Series.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The three divisional winners, seeded 1–3, and a fourth team — the Wild Card Game winner — played in two series.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Under sponsorship agreements with T-Mobile, the series was formally known as the **American League Division Series presented by T-Mobile**.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Astros and Red Sox won their respective series, to advance to the Championship Series.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This is the first time since 1999 that all four ALDS participants from the previous year returned to the ALDS this year.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Red Sox went on to defeat the Astros in the ALCS, then win the 2018 World Series over the National League champion Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Red Sox entered the ALDS as the 1 seed, having won the AL East with the best regular season with a record of 108–54, giving them home-field advantage throughout the entire playoffs.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The second-seeded Astros won the AL West, going 103–59.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The AL Central champion Indians were seeded third via their 91–71 record.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The final participant was the winner of the AL Wild Card Game, the Yankees.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This was the 13th ALDS appearance for Boston and the third appearance for Houston; the Red Sox lost to the Astros in the 2017 ALDS.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This was the 10th ALDS appearance for Cleveland and the 20th appearance for New York; the Indians lost to the Yankees in the 2017 ALDS.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This was the first season ever three teams finished with 100-wins in the same league.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Red Sox and Yankees met 19 times during the regular season, with Boston winning 10 of the games; this was the first postseason meeting between the two rivals since the famed 2004 ALCS, which Boston took in seven games after falling behind 3–0 en route to its first World Series title in 86 years.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Astros and Indians met seven times during the regular season, with Houston holding a 4–3 edge; this was the first time the teams met in postseason play.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This was the fourth postseason meeting between the storied rivals and their first meeting in the ALDS.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Yankees previously won the 1999 ALCS and 2003 ALCS, while the Red Sox won the 2004 ALCS.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This was just the 11th postseason match-up to feature two 100-win teams.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The ceremonial first pitch was thrown by former Red Sox outfielder Trot Nixon.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Martinez hit a three-run home run in the bottom of the first inning.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The lead grew to 5–0 in the bottom of the third, on a double, bunt single, single, and sacrifice fly.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Yankees scored twice in the top of the sixth, on three singles and a fielder's choice.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Red Sox reliever Brandon Workman prevented more damage by striking out Gleyber Torres with the bases loaded and two outs.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] New York added an additional run in the top of the seventh, with two singles, a walk, and a fielder's choice; Boston reliever Matt Barnes allowed only one run after the Yankees has the bases loaded with nobody out.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Aaron Judge led off the top of the ninth with a home run off of Boston closer Craig Kimbrel, but Kimbrel then struck out the next three batters to secure the 5–4 Red Sox victory.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The ceremonial first pitch was thrown by Steve Horgan of the Boston Police Department, who gained notoriety as the "bullpen cop" during Game 2 of the 2013 ALCS.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] A home run by Aaron Judge in the first inning gave New York an early 1–0 lead.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] In the second inning, Gary Sánchez homered, and Boston starter David Price gave up a pair of two-out walks followed by an RBI single from Andrew McCutchen, ending Price's outing after 1+2⁄3 innings, having allowed three runs on three hits.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Xander Bogaerts' home run in the bottom of the fourth reduced the Yankees' lead to 3–1.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] A three-run homer by Sánchez in the top of the seventh, his second of the game, doubled New York's score to 6–1.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the seventh, a single by Mitch Moreland and an RBI double by Ian Kinsler got Boston within four runs, 6–2.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Red Sox were unable to score again, with Yankees' relievers Zach Britton and Aroldis Chapman getting the final six outs.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] New York starter Masahiro Tanaka pitched five innings, allowing one run on three hits and getting the win, tying the series at one all.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Boston got on the board in the top of the second inning, with Rafael Devers scoring from third on a two-out infield single by Christian Vázquez.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The lead was extended to 3–0 in the third, with the Red Sox getting two runs on two singles, a sacrifice fly, another single, and a fielder's choice.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Boston broke the game open in the fourth, sending 11 men to the plate and getting seven runs on six hits, as Yankees starter Luis Severino was pulled for Lance Lynn who in turn was relieved by Chad Green.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Brock Holt had two hits in the inning, while Andrew Benintendi drove in three runs with a bases clearing double.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Yankees got one run back in the bottom of the fourth, on two singles and a fielder's choice.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Boston made it 11–1 in the top of the seventh, on a J.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Martinez RBI single, then 14–1 in the top of the eighth, getting three runs on a total of four hits, a walk, and a wild pitch.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Yankees catcher Austin Romine pitched the top of the ninth inning, allowing a two-run homer to Holt, who completed the first postseason cycle in Major League history.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Red Sox starter Nathan Eovaldi pitched seven innings, allowing one run on five hits and getting the win.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Yankees starter Luis Severino pitched three innings, allowing six runs on seven hits and taking the loss.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] First base umpire Ángel Hernández had three calls overturned in the first four innings of the game.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The defeat marks the Yankees' worst loss in postseason history.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The ceremonial first pitch was thrown by former Yankee Bucky Dent.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Boston took a 3–0 lead in the top of the third inning, on a hit by pitch, single, J.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Martinez sacrifice fly, Ian Kinsler RBI double, and an Eduardo Núñez RBI single.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] A Christian Vázquez home run in the fourth extended the lead to 4–0.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] New York got a run back in the bottom of the fifth, on two hits followed by a sacrifice fly from Brett Gardner.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Boston's Game 1 starting pitcher, Chris Sale, made a relief appearance in the bottom of the eighth, retiring the side in order.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Red Sox closer Craig Kimbrel entered to pitch the bottom of the ninth inning, allowing a leadoff walk to Aaron Judge followed by a single by Didi Gregorius, bringing the tying run to the plate.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Kimbrel struck out Giancarlo Stanton, but walked Luke Voit to load the bases, and hit Neil Walker to force in a run.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Gary Sánchez worked a full count before hitting a sacrifice fly that scored Gregorius from third.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Gleyber Torres then grounded out, ending the game; the call was confirmed by video replay.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Boston starter Rick Porcello allowed one run off of four hits in five innings for the win.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] New York starter CC Sabathia allowed three runs off of five hits in three innings, taking the loss.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] 2018 ALDS (3–1): Boston Red Sox defeated New York Yankees.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This was the first postseason meeting between the Astros and Indians.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Former Astros pitcher Mike Scott, the 1986 NLCS MVP and Cy Young Award winner, threw the ceremonial first pitch.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The defending World Series champion Astros began their title defense in strong fashion as Justin Verlander threw 5+1⁄3 innings with 7 strikeouts and 2 earned runs, holding the Indians hitless until the 6th inning.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] He and Corey Kluber traded hitless innings through the 3rd, before Alex Bregman led off the bottom of the 4th with a home run while Josh Reddick added an RBI single to bring the score to 2–0.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] George Springer and Jose Altuve hit back to back home runs in the bottom of the 5th and ended Kluber's day after 4+2⁄3 innings.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] After throwing five innings of no-hit ball, the Indians chased Verlander in the 6th after loading the bases.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Ryan Pressly came in relief allowing Yan Gomes to score on a wild pitch and Francisco Lindor on a José Ramírez groundout before striking out Edwin Encarnación to end the threat and keep the score at 4–2.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Martin Maldonado homered and Bregman drove in his second run of the day in the 7th while Reddick added another RBI single in the 8th to bring the score to 7–2.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Roberto Osuna closed the door in the 9th to give the Astros a dominant Game 1 victory.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Springer's home run tied him with Carlos Beltrán for the club record for most consecutive postseason games with a home run, with five.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Springer had four in a row in the 2017 World Series.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Three-time Astros All-Star and 2005 NLCS MVP Roy Oswalt threw the ceremonial first pitch.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Hoping to even the series before returning home, Cleveland struck first and took a 1–0 lead in the top of the third inning, on a home run by Francisco Lindor.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the sixth, an infield single and walk followed by a Marwin González double gave Houston a 2–1 lead.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] A home run by Alex Bregman in the seventh inning extended Houston's lead to 3–1.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] With two outs in the top of the ninth inning, a walk to Edwin Encarnación brought Josh Donaldson to the plate as the tying run, but closer Roberto Osuna got him to fly out, securing Game 2 for the Astros.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Houston starter Gerrit Cole struck out 12 and allowed just one run in seven innings for the win, while Indians starter Carlos Carrasco gave up six hits and two runs in 5+1⁄3 innings and took the loss.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Cole became only the second pitcher in playoff history to strikeout at least 12 batters without allowing a walk, following Tom Seaver's 13 strikeout-no walk performance in the 1973 NLCS.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Osuna recorded a four-out save for his third career postseason save, and first with the Astros.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Cleveland took a 1–0 lead in the third inning, on two singles followed by a sacrifice bunt and a sacrifice fly.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The teams traded home runs in the fifth inning, by George Springer of the Astros and then Francisco Lindor of the Indians.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Houston went ahead, 4–2, with three runs in the seventh from two singles, a fielder's choice, error, walk, and a two-RBI double by Marwin González.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Astros added six runs in the eighth on a homer by Springer, a double, two walks, RBI single, bases loaded wild pitch, and a three-run homer by Carlos Correa.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Houston extended their lead to 11–2 in the ninth, on a walk, balk, ground out, and RBI single by Alex Bregman.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Cleveland got one run in the last of the ninth, with Edwin Encarnación scoring from third on a wild pitch, followed by Melky Cabrera grounding out to first for the 11–3 final and to give the Astros a series sweep.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Houston starter Dallas Keuchel had a no decision after allowing two runs on four hits in five innings; he was relieved by Collin McHugh who pitched two innings without allowing a hit and got the win.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Cleveland starter Mike Clevinger also had a no decision after allowing three hits and one run in five innings; he was relieved by Trevor Bauer who allowed four hits and three runs (two earned) in 1+1⁄3 innings and took the loss.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] With their victory in Game 3, the Astros earned a postseason sweep for the first time in franchise history, advancing to the ALCS to meet the winner of the Red Sox and Yankees series.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] This marks the second time in franchise history that the Astros have reached back-to-back Championship Series; the first time was in 2004 and 2005, when the team played in the National League.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] The Indians were swept in the postseason for the first time since 1954, and were eliminated in the ALDS for the second straight year.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] They were also eliminated from the postseason at home for the third straight year.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] According to Jeff Passan of Yahoo Sports, the Cleveland Indians warned the Boston Red Sox that a man representing the Houston Astros might try to steal signs from their dugout in the ALCS.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] Passan reported that the same man, Astros' intern Kyle McLaughlin, was found taking cell phone video of the Indians' dugout during the Astros' and Indians' ALDS matchup.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] After the 2019 season, MLB punished the Astros for illicitly stealing their opponents' signs and relaying it to their hitters throughout 2017 and 2018 seasons.
[src:pitcher/2018-american-league-division-series] 2018 ALDS (3–0): Houston Astros defeated Cleveland Indians.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] The **2021 sticky stuff controversy** arose in Major League Baseball (MLB) around pitchers' use of foreign substances, such as the resin-based Spider Tack, to improve their grip on the baseball and the spin rate on their pitches.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] On June 15, 2021, MLB announced a new policy whereby any player caught using foreign substances on baseballs would receive a 10-game suspension.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] The policy also included umpire inspections of all pitchers during games starting on June 21, a decision that was met with mixed reactions from players and coaches.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Throughout the history of Major League Baseball (MLB), pitchers have used various methods of "doctoring" the baseball, using foreign substances or physically altering the shape of the ball to increase a certain aspect.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] An early example would be the spitball, which was popularized by Elmer Stricklett in the early 1900s.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] The spitball was formally banned in 1920, after Ray Chapman was struck in the head and killed by one such pitch.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Another historical method of doctoring pitches included the emery ball, in which sandpaper or an emery board was used to scuff one side of a ball and change its flight pattern.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] In 2012, Tampa Bay Rays pitcher Joel Peralta came under fire when he was found to be using pine tar to improve his grip while pitching.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Peralta was caught using pine tar in his glove during a game against the Washington Nationals, was expelled from the game, and received an additional eight-game suspension.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Peralta argued that he had been using the pine tar for batting practice, where the substance is allowed for help gripping the bat, and that "It's not like I'm using pine tar my whole career".
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] In 2009, professional strength athletes James Deffinbaugh and Michael Caruso began working on a substance that would allow weightlifters and bodybuilders to better grip the large, awkwardly-shaped lifting stones used during World's Strongest Man competitions.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] They developed a resin-based substance that the pair began marketing commercially in 2010 as Spider Tack.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] In addition to strongman competitions, Spider Tack became popular in the wheelchair sports community, as the tackiness of the substance helped athletes maintain their grip on the wheels of their chair.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] MLB undertook an informal poll during the 2020–21 offseason, during which they found that a majority of field managers considered foreign substances to be the most urgent issue in the sport.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] At the beginning of the 2021 MLB season, umpires and other officials collected baseballs from teams and analyzed them in an independent laboratory.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Simultaneously, the league-wide batting average at the start of the 2021 season was .237, the lowest that it had been since 1968.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] There were, on average, 8.98 strikeouts per team per game, the highest in MLB history, and pitchers had thrown six no-hitters by June 12.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] By mid May 2021, several batters began speaking out against the use of Spider Tack and other sticky substances.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] On June 5, 2021, third baseman Josh Donaldson of the Minnesota Twins accused New York Yankees pitcher Gerrit Cole of using Spider Tack.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] He noted that, in Cole's first start after MLB announced a crackdown on foreign substances, the spin rate on Cole's pitches dropped by up to 125 RPM.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] After the press conference, Cole clarified that his hesitation was because he did not believe that Zoom was the appropriate forum to discuss the issue.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Meanwhile, his Yankees teammate Jameson Taillon admitted that he had tried Spider Tack while recovering from Tommy John surgery, but that he had struggled to pitch with the substance and thus no longer uses it.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Donaldson threatened to expose "an entire catalog of cheating videos" of pitchers that he believed to be using foreign substances, before telling reporters that he wanted umpires to check "every half-inning" for non-compliance.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] A video from Hey_Commy, entitled “Josh Donaldson’s cheating catalogue” went viral on TikTok later that week.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] On June 15, 2021, MLB issued a press release announcing new guidance regarding "a uniform standard for the consistent application of the rules, including regular checks of all pitchers regardless of whether an opposing club's manager makes a request".
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Included in MLB's announcement was a mandate for routine, random checks of all pitchers by umpires in the Major and Minor Leagues, with any player found to have a foreign substance immediately ejected and suspended for 10 games.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] The rosin bags that are placed behind the pitching mound were allowed to remain, but pitchers were not allowed to combine rosin with other substances, such as sunscreen.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Enforcement across MLB began on June 21.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] On June 27, Seattle Mariners left-hander Hector Santiago became the first player ejected under MLB's heightened enforcement, after umpires discovered a foreign substance on his glove.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Both Santiago and Mariners manager Scott Servais said that Santiago was only using rosin, which is allowed, and that it had become sticky when mixed with his sweat.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] MLB announced a 10-game suspension for Santiago on June 29, which Santiago appealed.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Caleb Smith of the Arizona Diamondbacks was the second pitcher to be suspended under the new policy; umpires found suspicious material inside Smith's glove on August 18, during a game against the Phillies.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] He appealed the suspension, arguing that the substance was an accidental combination of rosin and dirt.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Under the new policy, Smith would have faced a suspension regardless.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Some individuals have argued against MLB's blanket ban on grip-enhancing substances.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] After Phillies pitcher Vince Velasquez lost control of a pitch, fracturing Washington Nationals pitcher Austin Voth's nose as a result, Nationals manager Dave Martinez argued that the injury could have been prevented had Velasquez been allowed to use a substance to increase his grip.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Martinez told reporters, "I understand them trying to clean some stuff up.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] But it's hot, it's slippery, it's sweaty.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Nationals general manager Mike Rizzo called Glasnow "courageous" for admitting to using grip-enhancing techniques and criticized MLB for the sudden ban.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] The process of being checked for sticky substances has been met with scrutiny.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Dodgers pitcher Clayton Kershaw suggested that an opposing manager should face punishment if he requests a substance check and the pitcher is clean, while Oakland Athletics reliever Sergio Romo, frustrated with the regular checks for foreign substances, dropped his pants in protest.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Most notably, Phillies manager Joe Girardi and Nationals pitcher Max Scherzer clashed when Girardi requested that umpires perform a substance check on Scherzer.
[src:pitcher/2021-sticky-stuff-controversy] Girardi was ultimately ejected from the game.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] Drafted by the San Francisco Giants in the 6th round of the 1992 Major League Baseball draft, he spent the first three seasons of his Major League career with them (2000–2002), compiling a 10–5 record in 167 games played (181.2 innings pitched).
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] He struck out Mike Redmond swinging for his first major league strikeout.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] From there, he began his career as a journeyman pitcher, trying to find his niche out of someone's bullpen.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] For the Texas Rangers (2003), he had little success, with only a 1–3 record and an earned run average just above 5.00.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] His next stop was the Minnesota Twins, for whom he had a .500 record (3-3), but an ERA still above 5.00.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] In the 2005 season, he settled into his role as the left-handed specialist in the bullpen of the Philadelphia Phillies and promptly proceeded to toss career numbers, posting a 4–0 record and an ERA of 2.24.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] Fultz was then re-signed by Philadelphia to a one-year contract for the 2006 season.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] Fultz was signed by the Cleveland Indians to a one-year contract before the 2007 season.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] The contract also included a club option for 2008.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] Fultz worked as a left-handed specialist in 2007, appearing in 49 games and going 4–3 with a 2.92 ERA.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] Before the 2008 season, Fultz's club option was picked up by the Indians.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] Yet on March 24, 2008, it was announced that Fultz would not be making the team after a poor spring.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] He put up an 11.88 ERA in seven games and gave 14 runs on 16 hits in 81⁄3 innings.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] The following day, Fultz was designated for assignment and was released on March 28.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] On March 29, 2008, Fultz signed a minor league contract with the Detroit Tigers, but asked to be released by the team less than 3 weeks after signing the contract because he wasn't called up to the team.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] On May 6, 2008, Fultz signed a minor league contract with the Colorado Rockies but was released in June.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] He subsequently signed with the Somerset Patriots of the independent Atlantic League.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] On July 20, Fultz made a start for the Patriots against the Bridgeport Bluefish and allowed 5 runs in the 1st inning.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] He settled down in the following innings allowing just 1 run in the 4th but was saddled with the loss.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] On September 9, 2008, Fultz's contract was purchased by Uni-President 7-Eleven Lions of Taiwan's CPBL.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] On December 21, 2008, the Cincinnati Reds signed Fultz to a minor league contract.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] Aaron was then released from said contract on March 23, 2009.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] On May 21, 2009, Fultz signed with the Newark Bears of the independent Atlantic League of Professional Baseball.
[src:pitcher/aaron-fultz] He retired from professional baseball on June 6, 2009.
[src:pitcher/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:pitcher/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:pitcher/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:pitcher/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:pitcher/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:pitcher/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:pitcher/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In baseball, the **pitcher** is the player who throws ("pitches") the baseball from the pitcher's mound toward the catcher to begin each play, with the goal of retiring a batter, who attempts to either make contact with the pitched ball or draw a walk.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In the defensive numbering system used in baseball, the pitcher is assigned the number 1.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The pitcher is often considered the most important player on the defensive side of the game, and as such is situated at the right end of the defensive spectrum.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] There are many different types of pitchers, such as the starting pitcher, relief pitcher, middle reliever, lefty specialist, setup man, and the closer.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Starting in 1973 with the American League and spreading to further leagues throughout the 1980s and 1990s, the hitting duties of the pitcher have generally been given over to the position of designated hitter, a cause of some controversy.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The National League adopted the designated hitter in 2022; as of 2026, the Japanese Central League is the highest level of competition to not use the designated hitter position.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In most cases, the objective of the pitcher is to deliver the pitch to the catcher without allowing the batter to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A successful pitch is delivered in such a way that the batter either allows the pitch to pass through the strike zone, swings the bat at the ball and misses it, or hits the ball poorly (resulting in a pop fly or ground out).
[src:pitcher/pitcher] If the batter elects not to swing at the pitch, it is called a *strike* if any part of the ball passes through the strike zone and a *ball* when no part of the ball passes through the strike zone.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A check swing is when the batter begins to swing, but then stops the swing short.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] If the batter successfully checks the swing and the pitch is out of the strike zone, it is called a ball.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] There are two legal pitching positions, the *windup* and the set position or *stretch*.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Either position may be used at any time; typically, the windup is used when the bases are empty, while the set position is used when at least one runner is on base.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Each position has certain procedures that must be followed.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A balk can be called on a pitcher from either position.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A power pitcher is one who relies on the velocity of his pitches to succeed.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Generally, power pitchers record a high percentage of strikeouts.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A control pitcher succeeds by throwing accurate pitches and thus records few walks.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Nearly all action during a game is centered on the pitcher for the defensive team.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A pitcher's particular style, time taken between pitches, and skill heavily influence the dynamics of the game and can often determine the victor.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Starting with the pivot foot on the *pitcher's rubber* at the center of the pitcher's mound, which is 60 feet 6 inches (18.44 m) from *home plate*, the pitcher throws the baseball to the catcher, who is positioned behind home plate and catches the ball.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Meanwhile, a batter stands in the batter's box at one side of the plate, and attempts to bat the ball safely into fair play.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The type and sequence of pitches chosen depend upon the particular situation in a game.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Because pitchers and catchers must coordinate each pitch, a system of hand signals is used by the catcher to communicate choices to the pitcher, who either vetoes or accepts by shaking his head or nodding.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The relationship between pitcher and catcher is so important that some teams select the starting catcher for a particular game based on the starting pitcher.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Together, the pitcher and catcher are known as the *battery*.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Although the object and mechanics of pitching remain the same, pitchers may be classified according to their roles and effectiveness.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The starting pitcher begins the game, and he may be followed by various relief pitchers, such as the long reliever, the left-handed specialist, the middle reliever, the setup man, and/or the closer.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In abbreviating baseball positions, **P** is used as a general designation for pitchers.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] **SP** and **RP** are sometimes used to differentiate starting and relief pitchers, respectively, while **LHP** and **RHP** are sometimes used to indicate if a pitcher is left-handed or right-handed, respectively.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In Major League Baseball, baseball rubbing mud is used to condition game balls before pitchers use them.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A skilled pitcher often throws various pitches to prevent the batter from hitting the ball well.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The most basic pitch is a fastball, where the pitcher throws the ball as hard as possible.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Some pitchers are able to throw a fastball at a speed over 105 miles per hour (169 km/h; 154 ft/s), such as Aroldis Chapman, Ben Joyce, and Jacob Misiorowski.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Other common types of pitches are the curveball, slider, changeup, cutter, sinker, screwball, forkball, split-fingered fastball, slurve, knuckleball, and vulcan.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] These generally are intended to have unusual movement or to deceive the batter as to the rotation or velocity of the ball, making it more difficult to hit.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Few pitchers throw all these pitches, but most use a subset or blend of the basic types.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Some pitchers release pitches from different arm angles, making it harder for the batter to pick up the ball's flight.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Pitchers use several distinct throwing styles.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The most common style is a three-quarters delivery in which the pitcher's arm snaps downward with the ball's release.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Some pitchers use a sidearm delivery in which the arm arcs laterally to the torso.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Some pitchers use a submarine style in which the pitcher's body tilts sharply downward on delivery, creating an exaggerated sidearm motion in which the pitcher's knuckles come very close to the mound.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Effective pitching is vitally important in baseball.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In baseball statistics, for each game, one pitcher will be credited with winning the game, and one pitcher will be charged with losing it.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] These are not necessarily the starting pitchers for each team; however, a reliever can win, and the starter would then get a no-decision.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Pitching places significant physical demands on the body, with physiological responses during a game showing heart rate, oxygen consumption, and muscle enzyme changes indicative of moderate to high exercise intensity and potential muscle stress.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A full game usually involves 120–170 pitches thrown by each team, and most pitchers begin to tire before they reach this point.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] As a result, the pitcher who starts a game often will not be the one who finishes it, and he may not be recovered enough to pitch again for a few days.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The act of throwing a baseball at high speed is very unnatural to the body and somewhat damaging to human muscles; thus pitchers are very susceptible to injuries, soreness, and general pain.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Baseball teams use two strategies to address this problem: rotation and specialization.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] To accommodate playing nearly every day, a team will include a group of pitchers who start games and rotate between them, allowing each pitcher to rest for a few days between starts.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A team's roster of starting pitchers are usually not even in terms of skill.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Exceptional pitchers are highly sought after and in the professional ranks draw large salaries, thus teams can seldom stock each slot in the rotation with top-quality pitchers.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The best starter in the team's rotation is called the ace.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] He is usually followed in the rotation by 3 or 4 other starters before he would be due to pitch again.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, the ace is usually the pitcher that starts on Opening Day.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Aces are also preferred to start crucial games late in the season and in the playoffs; sometimes they are asked to pitch on shorter rest if the team feels he would be more effective than the 4th or 5th starter.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Typically, the further down in the rotation a starting pitcher is, the weaker he is compared with the others on the staff.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The "5th starter" is seen as the cut-off between the starting staff and the *bullpen*.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A team may have a designated 5th starter, sometimes known as a spot starter or that role may shift cycle to cycle between members of the bullpen or Triple-A starters.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Differences in rotation setup could also have tactical considerations as well, such as alternating right- or left-handed pitchers, in order to throw off the other team's hitting game-to-game in a series.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Teams have additional pitchers reserved to replace that game's starting pitcher if he tires or proves ineffective.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] These players are called *relief pitchers*, *relievers*, or collectively the *bullpen*.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Once a starter begins to tire or is starting to give up hits and runs a call is made to the bullpen to have a reliever start to warm up.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] This involves the reliever starting to throw practice balls to a coach in the bullpen so as to be ready to come in and pitch whenever the manager wishes to pull the current pitcher.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Having a reliever warm up does not always mean he will be used; the current pitcher may regain his composure and retire the side, or the manager may choose to go with another reliever if strategy dictates.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Commonly, pitching changes will occur as a result of a pinch hitter being used in the late innings of a game, especially if the pitcher is in the batting lineup due to not having the designated hitter.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] A reliever would then come out of the bullpen to pitch the next inning.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] When making a pitching change a manager will come out to the mound.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] He will then call in a pitcher by the tap of the arm which the next pitcher throws with.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The manager or pitching coach may also come out to discuss strategy with the pitcher, but on his second trip to the mound with the same pitcher in the same inning, the pitcher has to come out.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] It is considered proper etiquette for the pitcher to wait on the mound until the manager arrives, whereby he then hands the manager the ball, and only then he is allowed to leave the field.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Relief pitchers often have even more specialized roles, and the particular reliever used depends on the situation.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Many teams designate one pitcher as the *closer*, a relief pitcher specifically reserved to pitch the final inning or innings of a game when his team has a narrow lead, in order to preserve the victory.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] More recently, teams began experimenting with an *opener*, a relief pitcher who starts a game but only pitches at least the first inning.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Other relief roles include set-up men, middle relievers, left-handed specialists, and long relievers.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Generally, relievers pitch fewer innings and throw fewer pitches than starters, but they can usually pitch more frequently without the need for several days of rest between appearances.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Relief pitchers are typically pitchers with "special stuff", meaning that they have very effective pitches or a very different style of delivery.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] This makes the batter see a very different way of pitching in attempt to get them out.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] One example is a sidearm or submarine pitcher.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Position players are eligible to pitch in a game as well, this however is rare as these players are not truly trained as pitchers and risk injury.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] (For instance, in a 1993 game, Jose Canseco suffered a season ending arm injury after pitching 2 innings.) Plus, they tend to throw with less velocity and skill.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] For these reasons, managers will typically only use a position player as a pitcher in a blowout loss, or if they have run out of available pitchers in order to avoid a forfeit (the latter typically only happens in extra-inning games).
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The only regulation game in which *both* pitchers of record were position players occurred on May 6, 2012, when the Baltimore Orioles' designated hitter Chris Davis was the winner in a 16-inning game against Boston while Red Sox outfielder Darnell McDonald took the loss.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The pitcher's duty does not cease after he pitches the ball.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Unlike the other fielders, a pitcher and catcher must start every play in a designated area.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The pitcher must be on the pitcher's mound, with one foot in contact with the pitcher's rubber, and the catcher must be behind home plate in the catcher's box.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Once the ball is in play, however, the pitcher and catcher, like the other fielders, can respond to any part of the field necessary to make or assist in a defensive play.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] At that point, the pitcher has several standard roles.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The pitcher must attempt to field any balls coming up the middle, and in fact a Gold Glove Award is reserved for the pitcher with the best fielding ability.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] He must head over to first base, to be available to cover it, on balls hit to the right side, since the first baseman might be fielding them too far to the baseman's right to reach first base before the batter-runner can.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Except for the first baseman, the pitcher ordinarily has the shortest run to first base of anyone, and is the second-most-likely person to make a putout at first base by retrieving a fielded ball thrown by an infielder (typically a first baseman).
[src:pitcher/pitcher] On passed balls and wild pitches, he covers home-plate when there are runners on.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Also, he generally backs up throws to home plate.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] When there is a throw from the outfield to third base, he has to back up the play to third base as well.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The physical act of overhand pitching is complex and unnatural to the human anatomy.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Most major league pitchers throw at speeds of 70 to 100 mph (110 to 160 km/h), putting high amounts of stress on the pitching arm.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Pitchers are by far the most frequently injured players and many professional pitchers will have multiple surgeries to repair damage in the elbow and shoulder by the end of their careers.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] As such, the biomechanics of pitching are closely studied and taught by coaches at all levels and are an important field in sports medicine.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The overhead throwing motion can be divided into phases which include windup, early cocking, late cocking, early acceleration, late acceleration, deceleration, and follow-through.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Training for pitchers often includes targeting one or several of these phases.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Biomechanical evaluations are sometimes done on individual pitchers to help determine points of inefficiency.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Some players begin intense mechanical training at a young age, a practice that has been criticized by many coaches and doctors, with some citing an increase in Tommy John surgeries in recent years.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Fleisig lists nine recommendations for preventative care of children's arms.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 1) Watch and respond to signs of fatigue.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 2) Youth pitchers should not pitch competitively in more than 8 months in any 12-month period.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 3) Follow limits for pitch counts and days of rest.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 4) Youth pitchers should avoid pitching on multiple teams with overlapping seasons.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 5) Youth pitchers should learn good throwing mechanics as soon as possible: basic throwing, fastball pitching and change-up pitching.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 7) A pitcher should not also be a catcher for their team.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The pitcher catcher combination results in many throws and may increase the risk of injury.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 8) If a pitcher complains of pain in their elbow, get an evaluation from a sports medicine physician.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] 9) Inspire youth to have fun playing baseball and other sports.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Participation and enjoyment of various activities will increase the youth's athleticism and interest in sports.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] To counteract shoulder and elbow injury, coaches and trainers have begun utilizing "jobe" exercises, named for Frank Jobe, the pioneer of the Tommy John procedure.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Jobes are exercises that have been developed to isolate, strengthen and stabilize the rotator cuff muscles.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Jobes can be done using either resistance bands or lightweight dumbbells.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Common jobe exercises include shoulder external rotation, shoulder flexion, horizontal abduction, prone abduction and scaption (at 45°, 90° and inverse 45°).
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In addition to the Jobes exercises, many pitching coaches are creating lifting routines that are specialized for pitchers.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Pitchers should avoid exercises that deal with a barbell.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] The emphasis on the workout should be on the legs and the core.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Other body parts should be worked on but using lighter weights.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Over lifting muscles, especially while throwing usually ends up in a strain muscle or possibly a tear.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Other than the catcher, pitchers and other fielders wear very few pieces of equipment.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In general the ball cap, baseball glove and cleats are equipment used.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Pitchers may also keep with them at the mound a bag of powdered rosin.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Handling the bag applies a small layer of the rosin to the pitcher's fingers in order to increase his grip on the ball.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] Currently there is a new trend of introducing a pitcher helmet to provide head protection from batters hitting line drives back to the pitcher.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] As of January 2014, MLB approved a protective pitchers cap which can be worn by any pitcher if they choose.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] San Diego Padres relief pitcher, Alex Torres was the first player in MLB to wear the protective cap.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] One style of helmet is worn on top of the ballcap to provide protection to the forehead and sides.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] In softball, a full face helmet is available to all players including pitchers.
[src:pitcher/pitcher] These fielder's masks are becoming increasingly popular in younger fast pitch leagues, some leagues even requiring them.
